POP — Prompt Oriented Programming

«Maintain intent. Derive implementation.»

Modern AI agents are remarkably capable of writing software from natural language.

Yet we still maintain code as the primary representation of our systems.

POP asks a simple question:

«Why?»

If intelligent implementers can reliably derive code from a well-written specification, perhaps the specification—not the implementation—should become the software's source of truth.

POP is a methodology for doing exactly that.

---

The Core Idea

Traditional software development treats code as the authoritative description of a system.

Documentation exists to explain the code.

POP inverts that relationship.

Software intent is written directly as a collection of human-readable documents.

Implementation becomes a derived artifact.

Just as a compiler translates source code into machine code, an intelligent implementer translates software intent into implementation.

When the software changes, the intent changes first.

The implementation follows.

---

Why?

Code is an excellent language for computers.

It is a surprisingly poor language for communicating intent.

Understanding an existing codebase often requires reconstructing decisions that were never explicitly recorded.

Why is this service using Redis?

Why does this mechanic work this way?

Was this architecture intentional, or merely convenient?

POP encourages these decisions to be communicated directly instead of inferred from implementation.

The objective is not to remove implementation.

The objective is to stop treating implementation as the authoritative expression of design.

---

What POP Produces

A POP project consists of small, focused documents.

Each document owns a single area of software intent.

Together they form the project's authoritative knowledge base.

These documents are intentionally concise.

They communicate:

- what the software should do
- what has not yet been decided
- what implementation restrictions exist
- why those restrictions exist
- which document owns each concept

They deliberately avoid implementation unless implementation itself is part of the intended software.

---

The Methodology

POP treats software development as the progressive stabilization and evolution of intent.

Every change follows the same cycle:

1. Evolve the programmer's intent.
2. Verify that independent implementers would preserve the same meaning.
3. Verify that every product decision has an explicit intent state.
4. Verify that implementation restrictions preserve their reasoning.
5. Preserve readability and semantic density.
6. Revise until the remaining findings have been consciously acknowledged.

Only then is implementation produced.

---

Findings

POP does not produce errors.

It produces findings.

A finding is simply an observation that requires programmer attention.

The programmer may:

- resolve it
- defer it
- reference another document
- reject it

The objective is not the absence of findings.

The objective is the absence of unacknowledged findings.

---

Knowledge Ownership

Every important concept should have one authoritative home.

Documents reference one another instead of duplicating knowledge.

This keeps software understandable as it grows.

When concepts evolve, dependent documents evolve with them.

POP treats concept evolution much like traditional software engineering treats API evolution.

---

Working With AI

POP is designed for collaboration between programmers and intelligent implementers.

The implementer is expected to:

- preserve programmer intent
- ask questions only when product decisions remain unstable
- freely choose implementation where intent allows
- treat implementation as disposable
- treat POP documents as the project's source code

Implementation may be rebuilt repeatedly.

The POP knowledge base persists.

---

Scope

POP intentionally concerns itself with one thing:

Communicating software intent.

It does not attempt to replace every engineering artifact.

Architecture diagrams, balance spreadsheets, API specifications, performance reports, and other technical artifacts remain valuable.

POP integrates with them.

It does not seek to replace them.

---

Operating Profiles

POP can be adopted in different ways.

POP Native

POP documents are the project's source of truth.

Implementation is entirely derived from them.

POP Embedded

POP owns only the software intent explicitly assigned to it.

Existing project artifacts continue to own everything else.

POP integrates into existing projects without requiring a rewrite.

---

Manifest

«Intent is written directly as documentation.

Implementation is derived from it.

An idea is stable when different people understand it the same way.

A specification is stable when different implementations preserve the same meaning.

Humans and machines both reason better about complete things.

Instead of complaining about syntax, POP complains about missing ideas and unclear meaning.

Software is a collaboration between the programmer and their compiler.

Programming is the progressive stabilization and evolution of intent.»

---

POP is not a programming language.

It is not a code generator.

It is not another documentation format.

It is a methodology for making software intent the primary artifact of software development.

Everything else follows.